<td background="/lotr/gfx/mom/blu_05.gif" class="headerbg"><font class="h1font"><font color="#FFFFFF"><table cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0 border=0 width=100%><TR><td><font class="h1font">Tournament Reports</td><form method='post' action=''><input type="hidden" name="PHPSESSID" value="...328fedb22570524062aeb1303" /><td align='right' valign='bottom'><select name='select' onChange='go(this)'><option selected>More DeckTech Tournament Reports</option><option value='#'> </option><option value='/starwarsccg/treports/index.php3'>Star Wars: CCG</option><option value='/heroclix/treports/treports.php'>HeroClix</option><option value='/vs/treports/treports.php'>Marvel VS</option><option value='/lotr/treports/treports.php'>Lord of the Rings</option><option value='/magination/treports/treports.php'>Magi-Nation Duel</option><option value='/swtcg/treports/treports.php'>Ophidian 2350</option><option value='/magic/treports/treports.php'>The Wastelands</option></select></td></form></tr></table></font></B></td><td background="/lotr/gfx/mom/blu_06.gif"></td></tr>
	<tr><td background="/lotr/gfx/mom/whi_07.gif"></td>
		<td bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/lotr/gfx/mom/whi_08.gif"><font class="bfont"><font class="h1font"> Devonator in Aquia, VA 03/30/2002<br></font><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Overall Rating:</b> </font><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><font size='1'>(4.95)</font><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Author:</b> <A HREF='http://www.decktech.net/lotr/main/mpage.php?member=6495'>Devon "Devonator" Clark</A></font><font class="afont"> <a href='http://www.decktech.net/lotr/main/mpage.php?member=6495&sub=1'> (Subscribe to this member)</a><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Date Submitted:</b> April 2, 2002</font><p align='justify'><blockquote><font class="bfont"> Pre-Tourney Stuff (If you don’t want to read it . . . skip ahead.)<br />
<br />
Ahh!  It’s been a long time since I’ve competed.  As a matter of fact, the last LotR constructed tournament I attended was a tourney in Atlanta that I was dragged to in the hopes that I would buy into LotR.  Well, despite my 1-4 performance (Hey, I was playing with hand-me-downs), I am now a regular . . . though not in tournaments.  That’s what I get for living in happening ole King George, VA.  (Is that a little “Dueling Banjoes” I hear?)  Anyway, my ex-roomy, Travis Hoovestol, clues me into a store in Aquia that has LotR league nights (ironically sans league kit) on Thursdays--Game World.  I start to attend.  A month ago, I won the store’s Sealed Deck tournament, but this is the first constructed.  But what to play?  I have 4 decks--two of them made specifically for competition and two made specifically for fun.  But there’s a catch.  One of my fun decks proves to be on par with my competitive decks--Devonator’s Moria Family Album.  I ruminate at length whether I should play Running in a Ranger Wonderland or Moria Family Album (both on my member page).  They both have weaknesses: Ranger Wonderland vs. a really strong Moria deck and Family Album vs. a really strong Nazgul deck, but conveniently both decks play the opposing decks weakness, so I decide to play them against each other and to the winner go the spoils.  Through the first 5 sites, my Nazgul owns the Dwarven fellowship killing 2 companions and severely wounding a third.  Still, the Nazgul could never break through.  Then, as I think the Ranger deck is poised to win, Frodo gets overwhelmed at site 7.  Now, I’m a little bit wary of playing the Moria Family Album because it is just a fun deck and therefore a little unconventional (plus I happen to know that there’s a strong Nazgul deck at the tournament), but I decide it’s just a game.  I would rather lose the tournament having fun than win the tournament just trying to be competitive.  The Moria Family Album is in.<br />
<br />
Me:  Devon “Devonator” Clark<br />
My Rating: 1517 (see above regarding 1-4 in my only other tournament)<br />
My Deck: Devonator’s Moria Family Album<br />
<br />
 (Author’s Note:  Please forgive me if details don’t seem to make sense or are sketchy.  I did not take notes during the games.  Still, I’ll do my best to recount the games as thoroughly as possible.  As a result, this TR is long--6 pages in Word.)<br />
<br />
Game One:  Moria Family Album vs. Justin’s Nazgul deck (Arwen and Sam start)<br />
<br />
In the pre-tourney report, I made mention of how I knew that there was a good Nazgul deck at the tournament.  This is it.  And at the store, Justin is probably the one player that I’m most worried about beating me.  So, I expected to play him, but I was hoping that it would be later as opposed to sooner.  Well, the good new was that I was going to get to see if I chose the right deck.  The bad news was that I didn’t want it to happen so early.  Anyway, we start the game.  <br />
<br />
I bid 1.  Justin bids 3.  He opts to go second.  My site 1 is the Prancing Pony (specifically because of good Nazgul decks).  I start Gimli, Son of Gloin and Gloin, Gimli’s Dad . . . hence the name Moria Family Album . . . while Justin starts Sam and Arwen.  I draw a strong fellowship hand: Sam, Farin, a Hand Axe, Stairs of Khazad-dum, Dwarven Bracers, and a Flurry of Blows.  I add a burden to play the one copy of Aragorn (heretofore referred to as Rareagorn) in my deck.  I also play Sam and remove those two burdens.  Gimli draws his Hand Axe and puts on his Bracers.  Gloin starts reciting tales to Sam and Rareagorn.  They don’t complain, because they know better.  Gimli leads my fellowship to the hood--Bree Streets.  I guess Dwarves don’t watch the news because you and I know what happens when you walk through the hood at night.  Well, two Black Riders--Nelya and Enquea--roll up.  Rareagorn holds Enquea at bay taking two wounds but Nelya gets past him.  Sam jumps in the way and gets whacked.  Gimli stops the second attack, and my fellowship decides to stop for a moment to catch their breath.  Justin and I reconcile.  I draw Fror . . . hooray!  Justin plays Aragorn (also the Rare version, but his will remain Aragorn to alleviate any confusion) from his hand.  Sam removes burdens, and then the fellowship moves on.  I add a Moria Scout and Goblin Armory.  The Moria Scout getshimmer in the head for being out past bedtime.  Justin contemplates moving again since Moria is impotent at sites 2 and 3 but the draw of Ford of Bruinen is too great.  Justin stays.  Farin joins my fellowship.  He heard about what went down in the streets and comes equipped with a Dwarven Axe.  Farin hands the Dwarven Axe to Gloin and Gimli hands his Hand Axe to Farin (I didn’t want him to get overwhelmed by Nelya or Enquea). I move on to the Ford of Bruinen.  Ulaire Cantea waits for me there.  Then Attea joins Cantea wielding a sword.  Cantea steals Farin’s axe.  I realize that I made a mistake in my assignment because Gloin is power 6 and Cantea can’t discard Gimli’s Bracers . . . but it wasn’t a big mistake.  It just forced me to burn my Flurry of Blows earlier than I might have liked.  Rareagorn takes on Attea and takes a wound.  But rather than lose any more to Ulaire “I hate weapons” Cantea, Rareagorn switches his assignment for the second skirmish and dies, while Gimli takes Attea (14 to 7 with 2 in the pool).  Justin thinks he’s killed Gimli.  I exert.  Justin looks at me like, “Why?  He’s dead either way.” but when I discard the Bracer to prevent the wound, he understands.  I stay to get some much needed healing.  Justin adds “Rareomir” to his fellowship with Armor and moves on.  I play They Are Coming, a Moria Scout, and use the Ford’s text to play Ulaire Enquea for 1.  The Scout must have come looking for his buddy, but he suffers the same fate as he gets thwacked in the head by a ranger.  Enquea does his two wounds but it’s not a big deal.  Justin stays.  I heal at the Sanctuary.  Fror joins my fellowship.  He replaces Farin’s Axe with an Axe of his own.  I play an Endurance of Dwarves on Gimli and Gimli’s Axe.  Gloin adds another story about the Stairs of Khazad-dum to his repertoire, and I play Make Light of Burdens.  There’s another Dwarven weapon transfer that ends up with Gloin having a Dwarven Axe, and Gimli bearing his Axe and a Hand Axe.  Frodo exerts as I move on to the Moria Lake.  Justin plays Morgul Gates to reduce the cost of the Witch King, and then he plays Ulaire Nelya to increase the Witch King’s power and a Pale Blade, also.  Gimli takes on Nelya.  I exert to make Gimli power 11.  Gimli lops Nelya’s Wraith-head clean off.  Farin, however, is not so lucky.  He gets cloberd by the Witch-King.  I mean, a Pale Blade up the aaaanyway.  The Witch-King exerts to remove both of my stairs and the Make Light of Burdens.  Gimli fights him the second time and takes 2 wounds.  Justin doesn’t add much to the pool.  He simply moves and exerts Frodo.  I play Goblin Swarms.  Both Justin and I know that the name isn’t a lie.  They do, in fact, swarm.  The card is just a warning ;)  I play a Goblin Runner, a Goblin Scavenger, and a retrieved Scimitar on the Runner.  I draw a Goblin Armory which I play.  I Host of Thousands for a Moria Scout.  Aragorn takes on the Runner.  Boromir takes on the Scout.  Arwen takes on the Scavenger.  Arwen takes a wound.  The Scavenger stacks on the Swarms.  I discard a Troll’s Keyward, which prompts some unwanted attention from the TD.  (Hey, man, I know Justin’s a smart guy, but don’t give him a gift by basically telling him I have a Cave Troll in my hand.)  Anyway, I add a Hand Axe to Gloin and Till Durin Wakes Again, and then move on.  With 11 in the pool, Justin adds Toldea and Nelya.  Gimli adds Toldea to his assortment of Nazgul heads when he goes Jet Li on Toldea with a Flurry of Blows.  Gloin tales 2 wounds from Nelya.  I stay.  Justin adds No Stranger, Ranger’s Sword, and an Athelas.  He moves on.  I play my third Goblin Armory.  Scavengers basically play for free now.  I play a Runner and Scout from hand, a Scavenger from the Swarms, and put the eternal Scimitar on the Scavenger.  I play the Ancient Chieftain I draw and then go find the Flame of Udun in my draw deck.  Boromir blocks the Scout.  Sam uses a Hobbit’s Stealth to hide from the Balrog.  Arwen fights the Scavenger.  Frodo fights the Runner.  Aragorn fights the Chieftain.  Everything but the Balrog and Scout ends up on the swarm.  Boromir takes the second skirmish with the Balrog and only takes 1 wound thanks to his armor.  With only a Balrog and Scout hanging around, Justin decides to take his chances.  He moves to Dimrill Dale.  I don’t have another scout to really use the text of the Dale effectively, so I go ahead and play the Keyward from my discard pile by discarding a PATHS, Farin, and They Are Coming.  I play a Runner from the Swarms.  I play a Scavenger and put the Scimitar on the Runner.  I draw a Cave Troll’s Chain to go with the Hammer and Troll in my hand.  Ah!  The Dimrill Dale Cave Troll Value Pack!  Aragorn exerts to become Defender +1.  He takes the Scavenger and Runner to himself.  Sam takes the Keyward and dies.  Frodo takes the Scout.  Arwen takes the Scavenger.  Boromir takes the Troll twice.  Everything except the Troll goes on the Swarm.  During my fellowship, I add Sting to the Reluctant Adventurer.  I use it before I do anything else.  I see that all Justin has Shadow wise is a Blade Tip, Witch King, and Pale Blade.  I only have 4 companions.   If I move without adding to the pool, Justin will only be able to play his Blade Tip.  I add a Till Durin Wakes for free and move on.  As expected, Justin only plays the Tip.  Woohoo!  I get a site uncontested.  Justin heals at the sanctuary.  He discards his Athelas to heal Boromir and then he finds a replacement Athelas.  Justin moves on to the Anduin Wilderland.  This is where things get interesting.  I won’t describe it all.  Suffice it to say that Justin’s fellowship ends up facing 10 orcs.  He doesn’t seem too worried and starts separating the 2+ vitality orcs from the rest.  PATHS anyone?  He makes Aragorn Defender +3 with a Valiant Man and 2 exertions (at some point he added a Saga of Elendil).  He assigns all of the orcs that he can, and with what remains, I pile a second runner on Frodo to make Justin burn his PATHS.  I also stack 3 orcs on Boromir to overwhelm him with a 26 power.  Arwen dies from wounds.  Aragorn gets overwhelmed.  Frodo is all that remains.  The game is over, right?  I have the win easy, right?  Wrong!<br />
<br />
Without any warning during the round, time gets called.  Justin is at site 7.  I’m at site 6.  According to Decipher’s rules, I lose.  I’ve been in control of this game since our fellowships entered Moria.  If this game goes 5 more minutes, I’ll win with ease.  I mean, my fellowship only needs to survive one more site and then I’ll overwhelm Frodo, BUT according to the rules of the game, I “lost”.  BS!!!  Well, I get lucky.  Justin obviously felt the same way that I did, and rather than steal a victory when he had obviously lost, Justin forfeits.  Justin, you rule!  <br />
FW +3 (3)<br />
<br />
Props: Mad Props to Justin.  You are the man, my friend.  You have no idea how much that single show of awesome sportsmanship elevated your stock in my eyes.  I’ve got nothing but respect for you, buddy.  I hope to repay the favor someday . . . Well, not really, because that would mean you were beating the hell out of me when time gets called, but hey, if I do end up on the other end of a similar situation, I would gladly do the same.  The same goes for all of you people out there in Decktechland because I don’t think it’s fair to steal victories from somebody who has obviously beaten you.<br />
<br />
Slops: To Decipher for the crappy means of resolving timed wins.  First of all, assuming that both players are neck and neck all of the way to site 9, there are 15 moves.  That’s 3 minutes per move.  With the bid, starting fellowships, and opening hands, it’s simply not enough.  If you end up with one tough decision at any point on the path, your game will go to time.  And then you severely disadvantage any deck that isn’t a run deck.  It’s a crappy system.  I propose that Decipher should extend the time limit by 15 minutes AND change the format so that you count the number of skirmishes that your deck wins (both sides).  All you would need is two ten sided dice to keep track.  That would eliminate the BS timed wins/losses and make it easier to determine who wins in the event of tournament ties, because you could have a differential.  If you agree or disagree with me, tell me in the reviews, because I might draft a letter to decipher.<br />
<br />
Anyway, that was the most interesting game of my tournament performance.  It turns out that Justin has to forfeit another game later on, because he and three other people have to drop the tournament.  Dude, I’m sorry that your day had to turn out like that, although I am glad that we got to play each other.  Anyway, my next two game accounts will be brief, and the last account will be a little bit longer.<br />
<br />
Game Two vs. Bob’s common Boromir and Merry start with a mixed shadow.<br />
<br />
Bob had won his first game.  Bob looks about 12 years old.  Bob had come all of the way from Maryland to play in our tournament.  Bob had an underdeveloped shadow that couldn’t hold me.  I walk all over Bob.  This was an easy win, but I was glad to be able to mentor him a little, and when the tournament results came around and he finished last and got nothing for it, I was happy to buy 6 packs of MoM, donate all of the commons and uncommons and give him his pick of the 6 rares (he chose Verily I Come).<br />
<br />
Bob and I both bid zero.  He wins the coin toss and opts to go second.  Out comes the Prancing Pony.  I add a burden and get Aragorn, RotN.  I add Fror, a tale, and a Dwarven Axe from my hand and move on.  Gimli and friends move back into the hood.  [Shudder]  However to my surprise, He plays a power 9 Uruk-hai.  Aragorn takes two wounds.  I move on.  Ford of Bruinen.  He adds Ulaire Nelya and an Uruk Soldier.  I discard the top 2 cards.  Fror kills the Soldier.  Aragorn takes 2 more wounds from the other Uruk-hai and dies.  Gimli and Gloin both take a wound from Nelya.  I stay.  Bob adds Aragorn, KIE.  He moves.  I play Goblin Swarms, a Goblin Scavenger, a Moria Scout, and a They Are Coming.  He Intuitions the Scavenger and the Scout gets smacked.  He moves on.  I reconcile and play another Moria Scout and Scimitar, but to no avail as he Stealths the Scavenger skirmish and takes a wound.  I add Sam, a Dwarven Axe, a Stairs, and a Hand Axe.  I move to Dwarrowdelf.  Gimli exerts.  He plays a Sauron orc and a Thin & Stretched.  Fror kills the orc and I take a burden.  He plays MoM Gimli and Gandalf, moves and I add a couple more Orcs.  He Intuitions and takes a wound or two.   I haven’t stacked anything on the Swarm yet.  I play both of my Till Durin Wakes.  I also play Farin and some weapons.  Now, Gimli has a Dwarven Axe, a Hand Axe, and an Endurance of Dwarves; Gloin has a Dwarven Axe and Bracers; Fror has his Dwarven Axe; and Farin is unequipped.  I move.  He plays the common Balrog.  Gloin fights the first skirmish and takes two wounds.  Gimli takes the second skirmish and takes two wounds.  I move to Dimrill Dale.  The Balrog is discarded and every dwarf heals 2 wounds.  He adds a Goblin Patrol Troop and Ulaire Enquea.  Gloin skirmishes Enquea twice taking 2 wounds.  Gimli wins his skirmish with an exertion and a Flurry of Blows.  This causes a card off of the top because of the Dwarven Axe.  Bob moves on giving me 9 because of Gimli.  I don’t have any runners and he doesn’t have any elves, so there is no way that I can play an orc and the Balrog, so I have to settle for a Keyward and Troll with Hammer.  The Keyward ends up beaten by Merry with a Hobbit Sword and a Boromir exertion.  The Cave Troll kills Gimli and gets stealthed the second time.  Bob decides to stay.  I heal, add Sam, and move on.  He plays a couple of Sauron minions that I wasn’t too concerned with.  I take some wounds and stay.  Bob adds Legolas and Sam.  I play my first runner, discard for the Keyward, and play another Troll.  The Troll kills Sam and Legolas.  The Keyward loses to Aragorn who had newly found his sword.  It becomes clear to me that Bob will keep adding companions thus making sure that I never break through with the Swarm, so I double move to site 9 with minimal resistance.  Sam ends up paying the price, but I win with ease at site 9.  <br />
FW +3 (6)<br />
<br />
Props: To Gimli, Dwarf of the Mountainrace for shutting the door on the Balrog.<br />
Slops: To Gimli, Son of Gloin for misplacing his Axe (His Axe was 2 of the bottom 4 cards of my deck).<br />
<br />
Game Three vs. Mark’s Gandalf, The Grey Pilgrim/Moria Archer deck.<br />
<br />
I overwhelm Frodo.  FW +3 (9)<br />
<br />
I’m serious that’s all that happened.  There’s not much to tell.  Okay, I suppose I can give you a little more detail than that . . . <br />
<br />
I bid 0.  Mark bids 2.  Mark opts to go first.  He starts the Shire Lookout Point.  He pulls the Cart, stacks a few weapons on the cart, and moves.  I play an Armory and They Are Coming and am done.  He stays.  Well, I don’t get to pull Aragorn or Sam, but I did draw Farin in my opening hand.  However, it occurs to me that if I only add the 2 Hand Axes, he’ll only get 4 in the pool and there’s no way that he can do any significant damage to me with just 4 in the pool.  I move.  He plays whichever Archer costs 2.  I take a wound in archery and then stomp the Archer.  I stay.  Mark puts some more weaponry on the cart, plays Glamdring and moves.  I add 2 runners and a Goblin Swarms.  1 Runner gets sliced the other goes on the Swarm.  He stays.  I play an Endurance of Dwarves on Gimli and move.  He plays a They Are Coming and that’s it.  Mark moves to my site 4.  I get 4 in the pool.  I play the 1 Runner form the swarm.  I play a Goblin Scavenger pulling a Scimitar I discarded earlier.  Then I play another Goblin Scavenger.  Frodo gets overwhelmed at site 4 by a Scavenger and Runner.<br />
FW +3 (9)<br />
<br />
Props: To the Swarms.  It’s so good that it killed my opponent at site 4 . . . well, it has.<br />
Slops: 3 Orcs hardly classifies as a Swarm.<br />
<br />
Game Four vs. Steve Alwine’s Gandalf/Sauron Burden deck.<br />
<br />
I mentioned earlier in the report that 4 people would drop from the tournament.  Well, at the end of the last round, they do.  Now, there are only 6 players left in the tournament.  The TD decides with all of those that drop, this is the last round.  That means whoever I’m playing against should be a game for all of the marbles.  I am in the lead with 9 victory points.  Edward is in second with 8.  We’re both undefeated (Edward has a timed win), so I should play him in the final round right?  Wrong!  I play Steve Alwine who has 6 victory points.  Even if he beats me, I’d still place above Steve.  Funny!  Anyway, Steve is a friend of mine and he has an interesting dynamic (Steve, I know you’re going to read this, so please take any criticism I give as constructive).  Steve’s a very emotional player.  He’ll start a game with all of the confidence in the world, but the second one thing doesn’t go his way, he gets frustrated and starts making mistakes.  It also happens that Steve knows my deck and I know his, so it should be interesting.  We begin.<br />
<br />
I bid 0.  Steve bids 1 or 2.  He knows I like to go second, but he STILL opts to go first.  I think he chose that, because he knew I start the Pony and he had pulled his Aragorns.  Anyway, his site 1 is the Green Dragon Inn.  I tried to coach him against this Site 1 before the tournament, but he chose to stay with it.  Well, as I go to pull my Son of Hamfast, Steve complains that my bid was a meta choice.  Well, yes and no.  I bid 0 or 1 (as reflected in the TR) and I certainly wasn’t going to bid 1 against a deck that I knew was a burden deck, especially when the bids of 0 were working for me.  Anyway, I only bring this up because it results in Steve getting a little frustrated and he makes a big mistake right off of the bat.<br />
<br />
We reveal our starting fellowships.  Mine, as always, is Gimli and Gloin.  He starts Gimli and Arwen.  He plays Gandalf from hand (I’m pretty sure it was Rare Gandalf, but it might have been the Grey Pilgrim).  Gandalf has his own personalized walking staff.  He plays Gimli’s Helm on Gimli and moves on.  What did he forget?  Were you paying attention?  He forgot Sam!  I play 2 Moria Scouts and a They Are Coming.  Arwen takes a wound and Frodo wins his skirmish.  Steve stays.  I exert Frodo to get Sam, and right as my Sam walks out of the Green Dragon door, Steve gets pi$$ed because he suddenly knows what he forgot.  I play Gimli’s Battle Axe and a Stairs of Khazad-dum.  I move on.  Steve plays an Orc Scout and a Desperate Defense of the Ring on Gimli.  Gloin takes a wound and I stay.  Steve plays nothing and moves.  I don’t know if he chose to do this because he knew that I was playing the Council Courtyard or because he didn’t have anything to play, but in either case, he added nothing.  I responded with a Goblin Runner, an Armory, and a Goblin Swarms.  Steve obviously knew what the Swarms led to, because he started looking at a couple cards in his hand.  I can only assume he was thinking, “When is the right time to play this Sleep?”  The runner, of course, like so many Moria orcs before it at sites 2 or 3, gets smacked for its presumptuousness.  Steve stays.  I start unloading items from my hand, and since I’m at the Trollshaw Forest, I get to draw cards.  I add a Hand Axe to Gimli.  I add Dwarven Bracers to Gimli.  The Dwarven Bracers lead me to an Endurance of Dwarves, which, of course, goes on Gimli.  I play a Dwarven Bracers on Gloin and that leads to a Make Light of Burdens, which I play to get rid of Desperate Defense.  Finally, Farin decides to join my Parade of Midgets on their way to Rivendell.  Can’t you just hear them sing . . . “Oompa Loompa Doopidy Doo“?  Anyway, there are two uninvited guests at the Council.  Twilight Nelya and an Orc Assassin crash our little party.  Gimli starts Defending the Ring a little too desperately as he gets a second DDotR.  During the maneuver phase, I exert Farin and Gloin for Make Light of Burdens and discard the top 6 cards from my deck to get rid of the two Desperate Defenses.  Then, in the assignment phase, Steve tries to kill Sam by spotting two hobbits to make one skirmish.  I assign Sam to the exhausted (thanks to Desperate Defense) Assassin, while Gimli fought Nelya.  Gimli exerts in his hard fought battle, raising his power to 11, and adds the new Nelya model to his wraith-head collection.  Then, he tosses his hand axe to finish off the Assassin (Well, not really, it was the Battle Axe’s text that killed it . . . but it sounds cooler my way).  I stay so I can heal.  Steve heals at the start of his turn.  He plays Questions that Need Answering.  He then plays Barliman Butterbur.  Barliman retrieves his copy of Questions and he does it again.  Steve discards a copy of Barliman to heal Barliman and he moves on removing 2 from the pool but adding 6 leaving me with 8.  Steve knows that my site 4 is the Moria Stairway.  Actually, he’s somewhat intimidated by it because he got to experience first hand why my site 4 is Moria Stairway (Cave Troll+Hammer+Stairway=Damage +3 and fierce!)  Now, while Steve invites me to play the Cave Troll and Hammer, I only have the Hammer.  So, I play a Goblin Scavengers, which pulls the Goblin Scimitar I discarded for Make Light of Burdens.  That leads to a second Goblin Scavengers, but there are no more Scimitars.  I also play a Moria Scout.  But Steve’s deck wouldn’t suffer the same fate as Mark.  The Goblin Scavenger with the Scimitar lunges for Gandalf.  The Moria Scout rushes Arwen.  And the other Scavenger steps to Gimli.  Gandalf takes two wounds from his assailant while Gimli benefits from a Servant of the Secret Fire.  Arwen takes her wound, and after I’ve stacked on the Swarm (hoping to draw the Sleep so that I can play my spare copy of They Are Coming) Steve stays.  I add Fror to my fellowship, a Dwarven Axe for Farin and a Till Durin Wakes.  The two that I added for Fror gets pulled.  With 7 in the pool, Steve plays an Orc Ambusher, Morgul Warden, and a Thin and Stretched (exerting the Warden).  I assign the Morgul Warden to Farin and the Ambusher to Gimli.  Gimli chops the Ambusher in two and tosses his Axe at the Warden.  Farin, on the other hand, was not quite as devastating as I wanted him to be.  I thought that both Farin and Fror added 3 to power versus their chosen enemies, but Farin only adds 2.  For that reason, Farin was a 9 to the Warden’s 9.  I lost the skirmish instead of winning. As I realized my mistake, I tried to reassign, but I had already resolved a skirmish, so I relented.  I just burned the Flurry of Blows in my hand early and killed the Warden anyway.  Thin and Stretched will add the burden at the end of my turn, so I decide to move on.  There’s 13 in the pool.  Steve plays another twilight Nelya and a Band of the Eye.  Apparently, Gimli collects wraith-heads and Nelya is his favorite, because he exerts to kill Nelya, yet again.  The Band of the Eye beats up on Farin forcing me to discard a card.  The bands victory over Farin also leads to an Enheartened Foe.  The Band is fierce forcing Gloin to step up and defend his kinsman.  I have to stay.  My plan works as Steve Sleeps to get rid of my 1 Armory, TAC, and Swarms.  He also plays Strength of Spirits to prevent the exertion.  He knows he’s stepping into Balrog Territory.  This time, the Balrog doesn’t miss his entrance.  I play my spare TAC and the Armory I had just drawn.  I then play Scavenger from my hand, which (when I play the Scimitar) leads to another Goblin Scavenger (sans Scimitar).  Finally, I use the Bridge’s text to go get the big nasty Balrog.  Arwen assigns to the Scavenger with Scimitar.  Gandalf assigns to the Scavenger without.  Gimli assigns to the Balrog.  Servant of the Secret Fire assures that Gimli survives the first skirmish.  In the second skirmish, Gimli exerts to prevent being overwhelmed and then the Balrog clubs Gimli in the head splitting his helm in two, but doing no damage to Gimli himself.  Steve stays.  I exert Sam to remove last turn’s burden.  I move on to site 6 healing all of my Dwarves completely.  A Morgul Hunter comes a-hunting Morguls (What does a Morgul look like, anyway?) but he has to suffice for Dwarves . . . err . . . a Hobbit.  He gets joined by an Orc Scout.  The Hunter stomps on Sam, while Gimli slices and dices the Scout.  I stay.  Steve manages to replace Gimli’s Helm.  He also finally finds Sam, Proper Poet.  I play a Runner from my hand, discard 3 cards for a Scout from my Discard Pile, and play the Cave Troll and Hammer.  Gimli and Gandalf beat the runner and scout into a bloody paste, while Arwen gets squashed by the Cave Troll.  Gandalf holds the Trolls second skirmish at bay with his staff.  There are wounds everywhere.  On my turn, I draw Rareagorn and decide to hold him until site 8.  I move to site 7--Anduin Confluence--and am met with little resistance.  (I apologize that the last couple of sites for my fellowship lacks detail.  It all starts to run together in my mind.)  I remember beating whatever orcs Steve played soundly.  Gimli might have had to exert once or perhaps somebody discarded a Bracer.  I double moved to site 8 because I had Rareagorn in my hand and he would guarantee me the win.  At site 8, Steve had nothing to play.  Steve starts his turn and heals his companions leaving a wound on Frodo.  Now, you might have noted that I have seen very few Runners and Scimitars this game.  Well suddenly they show up.  I play my second Armory and play two Runners from my hand.  I play a Scimitar on one of them and that draws me another Scavenger.  I play the Scavenger pulling a Scimitar.  That gets me another Scimitar.  I play another Scimitar and that gets me a Cave Troll.  I’ve added 7 to the pool and taken out 3.  That leaves 14 in the pool.  I Host of Thousands to pull my Keyward leaving 11 in the pool.  I play the Troll and Chain giving me 4, and I play the Ancient Chieftain from my hand.  Steve concedes, as that’s just too much for his fellowship to handle.  <br />
FW +3 (12)<br />
<br />
So, I win the tournament but am not the only undefeated.  Edward wins his game but his timed win only earns him second.  I win the Foil Balrog.  Cool . . . huh.  I was glad to win with my fun deck.  It was well worth it, and I really feel like I earned that Balrog.  Anyway, I know you’ve come all this way with me and you don’t want to hear me ramble anymore, so here are the finishing touches.<br />
<br />
Props<br />
Do I have to say it?  Mega-props to Justin for your awesome sportsmanship!  You rule!<br />
To Bob for coming all of the way from Maryland just to be in our little tournament.<br />
To Travis Hoovestol for running an . . . um . . . entertaining tournament ;)  Just kidding.  It was a good tournament, even if I do think you shouldn’t have let Justin know I had a Cave Troll.<br />
To Dwarves and Hobbits for being small.<br />
To Sam and Rareagorn for taking the hits when I needed you to.<br />
To Gimli’s wraith-head collection for being extensive.<br />
To the Moria Family Album for being full of snap-shots of Dwarven @$$-whoopins!<br />
And finally, to all of you for reading my long winded TR and sticking with me to the end.<br />
<br />
Slops<br />
To Decipher for the crappy means of resolving Timed Wins.<br />
To me for forgetting everybody but Steve’s last name.<br />
To the Bree Streets and Ford of Bruinen for always getting my Dwarves’ friends killed.<br />
And to the Balrog.  Why?  Because, he’s flaming . . . well, he is!<br />
<br />
Thanks for reading my Tournament Report.  I hope you enjoyed it.  Sorry, about the brevity (sic).<br />
<br />
Devon “Polonius” Clark<br />
